cons:
- Not great operationally and no enablement available for us to do our job easier. We still operate with systems and processes that have been used when Wise was a smaller company = meaning you will spend 10x the time to do a task that shouldn't take more than a few clicks/seconds time; Beware: Spreadsheets everywhere, anytime, for everything... Admin could take 60%-70% of your workload.
- Not very open to changes. Running processes the way they did years ago because it made sense then...
- The autonomous culture could be a double-edged sword. It actually feels more of an excuse around the chaos that exists. It probably worked perfectly when the company was smaller but it's insensible to continue running a scaling business with the same techniques/resources that have been used years ago;
- Could do much better with incentives and benefits;

pros:
- Mostly nice people that you work with (but have zero time to actually talk to);
- Salary and benefits are ok;
- The office is modern and looks nice;
- It's a good experience to see how the company operates;
- 30 days of a notice period so you can get out soon after you find a better job.

cons:
- The job advertisement and the reality are very different;
- Personal development opportunities close to zero;
- The salary is average but considering the expectations, the workload and the stress, it is really not worth it;
- Soul crushing corporate job that is promoted as something super cool.
- Flexibility is actually only expected from the employees, you can't really schedule your work as you wish;
- If you like to be treated like a robot instead of a human being, it' a great place where to work.

- one's success at TransferWise depends too heavily on whether or not you get a lead who is actually a good person and skilled/experienced to lead. in short - too many weak leads overall, who hinder personal development;
- poor career opportunities;
- salary much lower than would be expected of a company of such profile;
